Check out @workingholidayspaces to see more of Whitney and Carlos’ work.

node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.text:
Let’s talk about hometown glory. After a few years trying out different cities, one couple moved back to the neighborhood they both grew up in—around the corner from each other—in Abilene, Texas. Fittingly, the architect enlisted for the couple’s reno of a 1959 residence was also a friend from high school. Rob and Blake Eagle’s return to their childhood block commenced with the purchase of a mysterious home, surrounded by century-old oaks and pecan trees, that they had always kept in their peripheries growing up. When the couple stepped inside for the first time, the interior revealed a convoluted layout and lots of dated finishes. “The house was basically a time capsule,” remembers Blake. “There were leather walls, built-in limestone mosaics, secret doors that led to hidden gun safes. It really was a blast from the past.” Architect @erlingberg_, who had joined the couple’s highschool at 16 after growing up in Norway, was the ideal choice to help revamp the faded home. “We have a love for Scandinavian architecture and design, and [Berg] has an equal appreciation for our Texan heritage and what we expect out of our living space,” says Blake. The result of this hyper-local reunion is an open, contemporary home that maintains the beauty of its original character. Swipe through to see what the home looked like before, and try Dwell+ at the link in bio for the full remodel.
–

node.text:
On the journey to transform this former car shop into an art studio, one self-described “single painter lady” picked up a few extra passengers. The repair shop, located in Berlin’s bohemian Kreuzberg district, was the perfect place for Nata Lee Hahn and her work—little did she know it would become much more than that. Within a year of beginning the reno, Nata Lee had met her husband-to-be, Caspar, and the couple had their second child on the way. “We were like, ‘Ah, we’re going to need to include a children’s room in there somewhere,’” the artist laughs. Luckily, Caspar managed to acquire the adjoining space, creating a 3,013-square-foot pad for the new family’s home and linked studio. As expected of a tired auto shop, the space was pretty decrepit—”a lot of humidity, wet bricks,” recalls @thomas__karsten, cofounder of architecture practice @studio.karhard along with Alexandra Erhard. But the unvarnished potential captivated the imaginations of all involved. “The space was just empty and raw, and it gave us the opportunity to go wild. It was like a playground of ideas,” says Nata Lee. Today, playful touches abound in the apartment, creating a mix of openness and intimacy. Perhaps the best parts of the final product are reserved for discovery—a “secret passageway” leads from the parents’ dressing room to the kids’ bedroom, just one example of the new home’s lively character. Take the full tour of the space when you pick up the new issue of Dwell Magazine, or try out Dwell+ at the link in bio.

node.text:
Sometimes, inspiration comes in very small packages. For this micro home in Poland, a vintage Swedish radio was the key. When architect Adam Pszczolkowski, of Desea Architects (@adampszczolkowskidesea), set out to design his family’s retreat in the community gardens of the Rakowiec district in Warsaw, he leaned heavily on nature, but also on the aesthetics of the little box. “It may sound funny, but the design was strongly inspired by an old Tandberg transistor radio,” Adam says. “It’s a simple, horizontal box with eye-pleasing proportions and wood laminate sides.” At just 376 square feet, the tiny home is defined by its radio-esque form, but it also boasts a strong indoor/outdoor connection thanks to massive windows that flood the interior with light and allow the structure to appear woven into the lush gardens. Raw plywood in the interior also adds to this connection between the indoors and outdoors. “This creates flow,” the architect says. “The house feels like it’s sunken in the greenery.” Tour the radio-inspired Warsaw Weekend Retreat at the link in bio.

node.text:
It’s here! The Dwell 24: Our annual look at exceptional emerging designers forging the future of furniture, lighting, and other objects for your home.
For three years, we’ve been asking every designer we’ve featured on the list to reply to a survey about their lives and work. And this year, for the first time, none of them chose the dictum “less is more” as a personal credo. San Francisco designer Viviana Matsuda went so far as to call out minimalism generally: “I think it’s very arrogant and has notes of classism.” At Dwell, we don’t wholly agree. But we appreciate the provocation.
It has echoes in the work of many of the designers in this year’s group. Several told us about how they spent time during periods of lockdown and isolation by going deeper into their practice, honing ideas, and focusing on materials or craft rather than responding to external influences or trends. And if this period emboldens us to, like Matsuda, challenge orthodoxies about what our homes should look like—and to listen to designers who have spent this time refining their distinct voices—we can’t think of a better way for us all to emerge.
Swipe through to see some the designers in this year’s #Dwell24 and head to the link in bio to check out the full September/October issue.

Somehow, through doors destroyed by woodworms, failing aluminum windows, and faded layers of paint and wallpaper, one couple saw the beauty within this home on Spain’s Tenerife Island. “The house was absolutely derelict,” says María León Ferreiro, cofounder of practice @five_oh_five_design with her partner, @eduardo.lopez.solorzano. “It was owned by the bank and had been unoccupied for years.” The house, originally designed by Antonio Pintor Ocete—the city’s past municipal architect who is credited for bringing modernism to the Canaries—was dripping with his trademark eclecticism, and the couple recognized it immediately. “Even though the house was in bad condition, you could see the potential,” continues María. “We loved it from the first viewing.” After a thorough renovation, in which obstructive walls were removed, interior doors replaced, and pistachio-lacquered aluminum windows were set in place, the home has found glory once again. “The balance between this weathered beauty and the new color palette creates a harmonious atmosphere,” says María. The result is a comfortable space that offers up delightful moments of joy and surprise. Take the full tour of the renovated Casa Estudio at the link in bio.

The standard for indoor/outdoor architecture is constantly taken up a notch—this time, it’s quite literally elevated. Situated on a steep site just outside Vienna, Austria, this cantilevered home by Dietrich Untertrifaller Architekten (@dietrich_untertrifaller) uses a massive overhang to maximize its view of surrounding vineyards, mountains, and the Danube River. “The goal was to bring the scenery into the house and make it a tangible experience,” say the architects. After entering the home through the covered patio created by the overhang, a set of stairs leads directly up to the glass wing of the home. This upper level contains an open plan living/dining/kitchen area on one end, with a library, primary bedroom, bathroom, and sauna opposite. Glass doors and a low-profile fireplace help emphasize the longevity of the home’s vistas. “Visual axes from one end of the floor to the other enhance the home’s generous and open impression,” say the architects. Head to the link in bio for the full tour of the House in the Vineyards.

This breezy beach house recently emerged from a years-long haze. “It was just a mess,” says architect Malcolm Davis of @malcolmdavisarchitecture when he first saw the home in Pacifica, a town just south of San Francisco. “But it had good bones, and a great view.” When the owners decided to move forward and work with Davis on a renovation, there was a common understanding: It had to exemplify the beauty of thoughtful simplicity. It couldn’t be oversized or aggressively modern. It had to feel classic, but also embrace life on the coast. Fit within a simple gabled structure, the result remains fairly low-key. “It feels like an unassuming beach house,” Davis says. “We added space, but we didn’t add mass to the street. It’s simple, but it’s also interesting to see how much you can do without impacting the whole neighborhood.” See how the Pacifica Residence finally gets its moment in the sun at the link in bio.

Well, this is probably the nicest fortress we’ve seen in a while. Echoing the traditional Portuguese alcáçova—an ancient form of defensive settlement found across the Mediterranean—the holiday home is a striking form within the arid landscape of cork trees and cow herds. “We were inspired by the concept of a house which is a fortress with a larger inner court; a trace of white chalk in the landscape,” says architect Paulo Martins-Barata, founding partner of Lisbon-based practice @promontorio.arch. “The Alentejo landscape, and this mountain in particular, is harsh, even desolate, but beautiful and poetic at the same time. It evokes a kind of existential solitude.” In contrast to the home’s blunt exterior, the owners’ aim was to create a welcoming space that could easily host large groups. "This house is made for fun, for joy, to party, and to join family and friends," says Martins-Barata. "Its interior and exterior criss-cross at all times, with everybody passing through the vortex of the house, which unsurprisingly is the kitchen." Take the full tour of Casa da Volta, or “Home of the Return,” at the link in bio.

This Brazilian home is a real two-for-one situation. Designed by architect Tito Ficarelli for his family, the home in São Paulo merges two distinct Brazilian architectural styles: while the facade riffs on the city’s tough-and-ready ad hoc influences, it is also defined by a cast-in-place concrete structure that nods to a tradition of tropical brutalism. The contrasting frame makes for a favela-meets-bourgeouisie moment that mirrors its interiors, where private quarters sit below the social spaces on the main floor. Tito calls it an “upside down house,” referencing a style more popular in the early 20th century. “It’s a functional home for our family, but it’s also a space where the public is invited in to see art exhibitions or site-specific performances.” See how Sunset House’s brutalist form opens up to casual and formal spaces alike when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

This home in Lithuania brings a whole new meaning to being one with nature. With a radical bermed design by architects Gabrielé Ubarevičiūtė and Giedrius Mamavicius, cofounders of architecture firm @after_party.eu, the structure takes a first step in mediating the relationship between architecture and the landscape within a previously undeveloped tract. “When we first visited the area, there were no houses around, only a blossoming meadow filled with bees and little insects,” remembers Ubarevičiūtė. “Knowing that it would turn into a neighborhood in the future, our main aim was to preserve what was already there and find ways to compensate for our intrusion.” To create a residence with sensitivity toward the site, the designers implemented a green roof that touches down fully on both sides of a terrace just outside the living room. “It creates a feeling of solitude and framing life within nature as if it’s a living room under an open sky,” says Ubarevičiūtė. Take a stroll through, over, and under the home—dubbed the House and the River—at the link in bio.

A flea market find kicked off the design process for this Cape Town home. Inspired by the patinated, exposed-brick designs in the book on 1970s buildings, owners Robyn and Clint Campbell showed the pages to their friend, architect Michael Lumby of @michael_lumby_architecture, who was otherwise given carte blanche to design the home. “Clint gave me a simple brief,” says Lumby. “Three bedrooms, two bathrooms, and a living area.” Lumby delivered a three-floor, 1,520-square-foot brick building that stands like a beacon—its curves nodding to the Art Deco heritage found in the neighborhood of Vredehoek where it stands. “The theme was to invest in craftsmanship and custom detailing rather than expensive finishing and materials,” Lumby says. One detail, a bathroom sink with an angled pane where water runs into the garden, is case in point. “If you give someone the chance to use their voice,” says Clint, who speaks from experience as a creative director, “they tend to really shine.” Tour the ‘70s-inspired Cape Town home when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

One couple didn’t have to search too far for an architect to help them with their Victorian revamp. Kate and Gary Westlake turned to Kate’s brother, Ben Minifie of @minifiearchitects, to help them reorient the home for their growing family. After extending the bedrooms of the teenage children—offering them better lighting and a shared bathroom, along with storage space and study areas—Minifie turned his focus to the family’s shared spaces on the main floor. By reorganizing the floorplan, the family gained a snug TV room and guest bedroom, all clad in plywood. An oriel window adds further coziness to the space as “the perfect place to sit and read a book,” says Gary. The extensive use of timber not only unifies the interior but also reaches outside, wrapping around a backyard to a new outbuilding that houses a home office, bar, and DJ area. Through the reno, the family has fallen in love with their home again. "How we use the house has changed massively," says Gary. "All of a sudden, partly due to lockdown but also because we now have all this well-designed space, we are spending more quality time together as a family."
